title: Suzuki DRZ 400 SM rear rotor guard (Motorcycle)

description.text:
This is a slightly beefier designed rear rotor guard for the DRZ 400 SM, it may also fit the S model, but they do use a smaller rotor and may have other differences.  
This is the 2nd design with extra reinforcements and some vent (mostly for style) holes. I printed this in regular PLA at 100 microns, mounted it on the bike, and kicked it a number of times. It appears to be plenty strong but I will be reprinting it again soon using impact modified PLA from Diamondage in New Zealand. From my experimenting on their raw impact PLA and Hi-Impact PLA, I suspect the part will be all but indestructible. While regular PLA is quite brittle (the filament can easily be folded over and snapped), the impact modified PLA takes some pretty extreme strain levels before undergoing a ductile fracture. I don't have enough to print up dogbones for the Instron, but I suspect it could easily exceed most ABS filament.  
The only real reason to print this is for aesthetics, the stock guard is the one cheap looking piece of white plastic on the bike.  
If you like the design, please "like" the design and post pictures of your completed copy or derivative.

title: Pebble Watch Stand (Including Bunk Bed Version)

description.text:
It's a pretty straightforward design. I made the bunk bed version first since I wanted a place to put my Pebble smart watch at night without having to get off from my bunk bed. The bed version is designed for beds with holes on the corners to support the rod for a bunk bed. I then figured I might as well just take the same fit and use it to make a version that can just stand on its own.   
It's designed for the original pebble. I have no idea if it will work with a pebble steel or pebble time, but anyone is obviously welcome to try either of those watches.   
I also uploaded the STEP files, so feel free to make any improvements.

I used PLA with .2 resolution and 12% infill. I'm sure you could get away with less though. I didn't need or use supports on either of them, although you might need some on the cylinder peg on the bed version depending on how well your printer can handle that. Both took about an hour on my Makergear M2.  
The charger for the watch fits into the hole, and that magnet is what holds up the watch. The charger mount on the ones I printed was tight enough to hold it easily, so it shouldn't be a problem.   
The platform the watch rests on has to be offset from the bottom of the charger a little bit because of the shape of the watch, and I'm pretty sure I've found the right distance to offset it, but you might have to play with it a little. I haven't really had any trouble getting the watch to stay on though.   
One other thing to note, I have two chargers. The magnets in one of them aren't strong enough to hold the watch up. So if the watch doesn't stay on, it might also just be the charger.

3º Se introduce la pieza corredera untada en vaselina para que deslicen bien las juntas tóricas por el interior del cilindro de la jeringuilla
4º Se cierra pegando la tapa

author: Chrisbot

title: Bowden extruder sponge-mount vibration dampener for NEMA 17

description.text:
This mount uses 2 household kitchen sponges folded 90* to tightly hold the body of a NEMA 17 stepper motor-based extruder, such like the Airtripper V3.
The sponges squeeze in between the inside of the mount and the body of the motor - the gap is 8mm. If you're feeding your bowden extruder with serious amps (especially if you have one of the longer-bodied NEMA 17's) you'll notice crazy vibrations coming from the motor, which if hard-mounted to the chassis of your printer can make theee most annoying sound in the known universe. You can't use the rubber mounting-face couplers with these extruders for obvious reasons, and using rubber standoffs can be a tricky trial & error process with the likelyhood that you won't find soft enough rubber. I was really surprised at the noise reduction this simple ghetto solution provides. In my case, a guess of about 80% less noise, I can barely hear it now.

1.6mm+ perimeter, 25%+ infill, mild cooling.  
Skirt is built-in for better adhesion and is part of the height, it's not a raft. The excess will snap off.  
The 2 holes are 5mm (M5)  
It's possible that the vibrations will walk the motor out of the mount if it's not angled, so either loop a couple of elastic bands around it to keep it in or mount it a few degrees from horizontal so gravity will help keep it in.

I picked up a few 12V LED lamp units designed to replace the halogen bulbs in under cabinet light fixtures but the normal bases are too big and bulky since they have to deal with the high temperatures. Here is a simple design that holds the "bulb" via integrated clamp. This design uses 2 M3 press fit inserts for the M3 screws to grab into, I suggest using 8mm length screws as the only ones I had were 10mm and they are a tad on the long side but will still work. A simple Molex 2 position wire housing works great for connecting to the light. Attached are the STL files and the FreeCAD files to edit as you wish. The M3 inserts can be bought from Grainger and the Molex housings and terminals can be picked up from Mouser. Inserts: https://www.grainger.com/product/GRAINGER-APPROVED-Press-Insert-4ZU25?s_pp=false&picUrl=//static.grainger.com/rp/s/is/image/Grainger/4ZE96_AS01?$smthumb$ Housings : http://www.mouser.com/ProductDetail/Molex/50-57-9002/?qs=%2fha2pyFaduh6M3JhjTACB17sRZCRrk8oHpIUpdMrRyL2HptJlAoKdQ%3d%3d Terminals : http://www.mouser.com/ProductDetail/Molex/16-02-0096/?qs=sGAEpiMZZMs%252bGHln7q6pm%252bS0pk2Wo0Xx7oS4OmuX%2foQ%3d

Printed at 20% line infill with 4 top and bottom layers and 3 perimeters.  Hot-End temp was at 225°C and the hot bed was at 110°C the whole time. Replace missing fan blades. Weird. I suppose that while they were remodeling these web pages, my original description was somehow deleted. Here it is again: One blade snapped off a 9-blade, 40mm extruder fan. I hate to trash a good fan, and considered applying an entire new ring of blades with the method loco uses here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:351835 But since only one blade was gone, I cut one replacement from a ring of blades. The file, blade ring.stl, was designed to fit over a blade hub with an OD of ~21.7mm. The blades have an OD of 36.5mm at their tips. Blade thickness is near 1mm. Suggest printing with the thinnest layers and slowest speed possible. Cut the blade(s) from the ring, and position it carefully. Rough up the mating surfaces, and attached it with 5-minute epoxy.
After the glue is completely cured, file away any excess material. Extra weight could make the fan vibrate.
Sharpen the blade edges a little, and generally smooth things out for good air flow.

description.text: This is a design of the RepRap extruder drive that is compatible with the Darwin quickfit clamp system and the Ponoko lasercut kit. It will take either 16mm PTFE or heatsink based heaters. It is designed to be made with no lathing or machine tooling. An opto sensor may or may not be fitted to regulate rotation speed - I found that this was definitely required with an all-metal heater assembly. If you develop software to do that, we'd love to see it!

The design uses a 50mm M5 drive screw which can be cut from an M5 bolt. Coupling is by an M5 grub screw lock-nutted to the top of the drive screw; a 2.5mm hex key replaces the Tamiya output shaft and docks with said grub. Filing the point off the end of the grub screw will make it easier to fit.
You'll need an assortment of M3 nuts, bots & washers to assemble it. Put springs under the 4 screws holding the filament and screw holders together so that compression is maintained as per the original RepRap screw extruder on the RepRap wiki.
There is a cavity in the screw holder to take another locknut and two washers that are used as a thrust bearing. The drive screw is also supported near the point of contact with the filament by half an M5 nut which has been drilled out to 5mm. With luck, anyone should be able to source these components worldwide.

title: SHELFIE | DIY parametric shelf and storage designer

description.text:
Shelfie allows you to design your own storage and shelf systems using a fully parametric design. Simply generate the required Shelfie connectors based on your preferred storage layout using the Customizer button or OpenSCAD directly. It is based on the original concept idea from Milla Niskakoski http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:681835 I was impressed with the simplicity and practicality of Milla's initial design, but ran into some limitations when trying to construct my own shelves. The key improvements are:
  • Customisable thicknesses. I wanted to use the scrap wood I had lying around rather than purchase new material.
  • Mixed thicknesses. I wanted to use glass shelves with wood sides, but it wasn't possible unless they were the same thickness.
  • Wall mounting bracket option. Particularly for tall shelves, this is an important safety feature. Wall brackets also support cross-bracing by connecting a tensioned line between opposite corners or adding a back panel.
  • Ability to alter the size of the bracket or the wall thickness to increase strength.
  • Ability to attach a shelf or divider mid-span or mid-panel. Allows use of longer shelves or supports for extra strength and adding a shelf or divider in-between.
  • Allow panels to butt up against each other to eliminate gaps.
    • Shelfie provides full control over all parameters so you can mix materials of any thickness, add wall mounts, alter the bracket size, mid mount shelves, change the screw hole size etc. UPDATED: v2 Added 'no internal bracing' option to allow panels to butt together and a corner radius cut-off option for wall mounting.

Plan the storage layout and the types of brackets required. Select the bracket type and options to suit your particular materials in Customizer and generate the STL file. The brackets are very easy to print and require no special instructions. 
Note: If you set the Base Thickness to '0', you can create brackets that do not need to be mounted on the panel edge i.e. mid-panel mounting.

comments.text: Do you typically use PLA or ABS?  Advantages / disadvantages of either?

comments.text: Both materials are fine. ABS is stronger and better for high impact or stress, but standard PLA is still adequate for most uses. Both are easy to print, although PLA is easier. Because it prints laterally along the key stress points, ABS still maintains its strength even if you get layer separation. You can also compensate for any weakness by  increasing the size and thickness.
